column169: It was reported a spill of about 1 cup of SSI 150 (UN1268), a petroleum distillate product by Solvent Systems happened at the XDP Terminal. The 55gal drum was punctured during loading by a forklift at the XDP terminal which caused the release to the dock when it was unloaded. Upon reviewing the SDS with the terminal, it was determined that the staff could safely clean the spill in the ventilated dock while donning skin/eye PPE, using absorbents, keeping the material away from ignition sources, and avoiding eating/drinking/smoking near the material. The undamaged product was transferred to a new 55gal poly drum. Total waste content, being the spilled product, empty drum, and spent absorbents, were put in the empty drum. The waste was left onsite for the terminal to manage.

Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged drum was placed into an 85-gallon metal overpack. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were collected into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On 11/6/2023 at approximately 1202, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 154002 at the station location in Temecula, reporting a package spill.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box containing two plastic cans overpacked into another fiberboard box.  One of the plastic containers spilled due to a loose cap.  Further inspecttion revealed that the inner fiberboard was labeled with Class 8 hazard label.  An online safety data sheet futher classified the shipment as UN 2491.  The outer package was not marked and labeled per IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held, pending an investigation by the FAA.

Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to the impacted area. MSES personnel then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in using hand tools. Crews utilized absorbent pads to collect any residual product from the impacted areas. The empty 5-gallon jug, all spent absorbents, and any cleanup debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and was staged onsite for future disposal.

column169: Delta received notification on 11/21/23 of an undeclared event where a UN0276(Cartridges, power device(squib)) shipped undeclared from Atlanta to New Orleans airport. There were five parts in total located in the shipment; one of which was hazmat. The original order for this shipment was for four non-hazmat parts. When packaging this box, the agent used recycled packaging material from a nearby recycling bin. The affected cartridge was intermixed within this bin. When the employee used the recycled packaging material, the cartridge was intermixed and unknowingly placed in the box.   Flight#: DL2224  Date: 11/21/2023  AWB: 006-80159914   The event is under investigation to determine root cause and subsequent corrective actions.   See the attached pictures.
column170: This event remains under investigation. The team is in the process of analyzing this event to determine root cause(s) and subsequent corrective actions. Comprehensive system corrective actions will be further developed upon root cause determination. Immediate corrective actions are:   a) Temporary signage added to the recycle bin requiring material to be checked for parts and paperwork prior to being placed in the bin and prior to being used.   b) Permanent signage to be order and added to the recycle bin requiring material to be checked for parts and paperwork prior to being placed in the bin and prior to being used.   c) Maintenance communication was distributed on 12/07/2023 noting requirements I   d) Review and update TOPP and SOP to cover the recycle process and signage requirement  -TOPP 60-70-05 Company Materials Shipment  -SOP Packaging  -TOPP 60-70-35 Routing Parts

column169: ALR Trucking arrived at the FedEx Trade Networks facility carrying cargo from Mexico destined for sortation and subsequent distribution in the U.S. Upon opening the trailer doors, it was discovered that one drum of UN1263 was Ieaking near the chime. Six(6) drums were loaded on one wooden skid(pallet) and were secured with plastic and metal banding and shrink-wrap. There were damaged boards on the loading side of the skid. The drum that was Ieaking had its chime fall between the boards, either during the banding process or during transportation. The constant friction of transportation caused the chime area to buckle into the bottom of the drum. The drums are not UN Specification as required in the regulations. We contacted our emergency spill clean-up vendor. They placed the 7 gallon drum into a larger overpack containment drum. The materials used to clean up the small amount that spilled were placed into a 5-gallon plastic bucket for waste disposal. Please see the accompanying photographs of the load upon arrival and the subsequent mitigation. While we do no have the final figures on the remediation, we believe the cost of the clean-up crew to average around $500 or more, and the disposal of the clean-up material to start at$250.
column170: Use of proper packaging by the shipper, and the loader securing the drums onto a pallet with a smooth wooden top would have greatly reduced the risk of drum failure during transportation.

column169: At 13:15 on 11/05/2023 a 500 Line Railroad (DBA CPKC) Hazardous Materials Officer became aware that  UTLX 220854 was leaking from its protective housing at the CPKC St. Paul, MN rail yard. A railroad  qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate. Upon arrival, responders identified that the release was emanating from the threads on the nipple,  where the liquid valve connects to the pressure plate. Responders could not tighten the valve  because the threads were cross threaded. Because of this, absorbents were placed in the protective  housing, around the leak to catch additional product and replaced daily. The shipper was notified,  and subsequently mobilized a Mobile Repair Unit (MRU) to repair the car. The MRU removed the  Nitrogen pad (5Ibs) that had been applied to the car at the time of shipping, which stopped the  leak. However, the MRU could not remove the liquid valve to repair the connection. Because of this, the Shipper applied for an OTMA to move the car to home shop. Both CPKC and UP  Railroads would not agree to this move, so the car was transferred and cleaned an purged in St.  Paul. Once this was done, CPKC and UP Railroads agreed to move the car under an OTMA-1 to home shop  for repairs. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at  the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the  exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column170: The 500 LINE RAILROAD COMPANY (DBA CPKC) notified shipper of this release. Continued emphasis with  Offerors/Shippers is made encouraging them to conduct thorough inspections prior to movement in  order to reduce equipment failures in the field. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating  on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail  yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and  both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non  accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct  a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective  action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with CPKC.  (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Ed Dankbar, 500 Line Railroad, 120 S 6th ST STE 900, Minneapolis, MN 55402. The shipper can reference http:1/nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column169: On November 22, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2693 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately fifty-five (55) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement underneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site.  FCE personnel utilized a pressure washer to the empty sodium bisulfite-impacted trailer and collected the impacted water with absorbents and absorbent pads. Crews collected and containerized the absorbents and absorbent pads into one (1) 55-gallon drum. All impacted pallets and cardboard were collected and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon drums and the damaged 55-gallon drum was placed into one (1) 95-gallon over-pack, all for terminal disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal LSL experienced a UN2920 Spectrus NX1103 release from a 5-gallon poly pail. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of material released to an 8’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and concrete lot below due to a forklift puncture. A soap and water solution was utilized to clean all impacted surfaces. Absorbents were then deployed to collect all material. The damaged jug and impacted absorbents were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged cut up pallet was placed into a separate 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted surfaces were scrubbed and treated thoroughly but still showed signs of staining, and all surfaces passed the water test. All other unaffected jugs were re-stacked to continue to the destination. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
column173: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column169: Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 10ft-by-30ft area of the asphalt/concrete parking lot, the trailer floor and concrete dock floor and estimated that ten (10) gallons of material was released due to forklift damaging one (1) 275-gallon poly tote. Enviroserve personnel gravity  transferred  the  remaining  product  to  a  new  poly  tote  and  the  damaged  tote  was  cut-up  and placed into one 55-gallon poly drum. The new 275-gallon poly tote was shipped on to the consignee.  Enviroserve  personnel  deployed  a  neutralizer  to  the  impacted  areas  and  then  used  a  granular absorbent to gather the spent material. column169: At 2201 this evening we were contacted by Export Dock agent Jorge Lazo that LH6751S/29 ex PHL came in with a DG spill. When the truck was opened there was liquid already spilled and shutters were closed immediately. We immediately cordoned off the area and called PAPD to report the DG spill.  PAPD Officer Farber (Badge#1829) responded at 2220 to investigate. PAPD ESU & Port Auth Ops arrived shortly after.  Hassan simultaneously contacted the 24HR emergency contact on DGD (Celinia @ NCEC) and was advised safety precautions, spill response and containment methods.  This was relayed to Port Ops and PAPD ESU.  PAPD started containment process with speedy dry at 2235 and completed at 2320. 7 of 36 Jerricans (AWB 020-69236160) were affected and stored in containment drums in the DG reject area. AWB: 020-43064475 was loaded next to leaking jerricans and was also wet/stored in containment drum. We also noticed that liquid had leaked from trailer to tire and ground.  Speedy dry was used to contain the leak. Safety-Kleen was contacted at 2323 for cleanup of contained spill and disposal.  Safety-Kleen dispatched a response team at 0105   Trailer is currently in Bay 52. Driver is onsite waiting on cleanup to leave.    IQSMS Report: 15387 PAPD Case: 23K302528 Truck number: 6751S/29NOV Driver name: Jose Deleon Provider: Forward Air Rcvd with Seal number 126350982 ex PHL.  Shipment packed in non UN specification package.
column170: As shipment was packed as overpack and shrined by black foil, it was not possible to see any discrepancies during acceptance process. The possible cause of leakage is the way how shipment was packed by shipper. Shipper stacked jerricans 3 high without using any planks or platforms in order to distribute weight evenly, in result lover row of barrels was deformed and damaged. Also, shipper didn't use UN specified package, this can be also the reason of leakage. This recommendation was given to the shipper. Official statement was requested.

column169: On November 14, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of paint was crushed in transit and released approximately one and a half (1.5) gallons of product to the loading dock floor and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Moran Environmental Recovery (MER) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized hand tools to scrape the released product off the loading dock floor. MER personnel utilized absorbent pads with a degreasing agent to collect any residual product from the impacted areas. Crews then utilized a rotary transfer pump to transfer the contents of the damaged 275-gallon tote to a new 275-gallon tote to be shipped off to its destination. MER personnel deployed granular absorbents inside the damaged tote, to solidify any remaining product, once the rotary transfer pump stopped. Crews then placed absorbent pads, under the damaged tote, and wrapped the tote in two (2) layers of poly sheeting to ensure any additional residual product was contained. All UN1263 impacted material was collected and containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

On November 29, 2023 at approximately 9:57 AM, a Plains transport driver with a load of crude oil was traveling southbound on NW 70th St near Byers in Pratt County, KS to Plains Wellsford Station east of Wellsford, KS. The driver ran off the roadway (right) onto the earthen shoulder, went to correct to enter back onto roadway (left) when trailer turned sideways and with momentum laid over onto its side. Upon landing on its side a seam on the trailer body was punctured, creating a small hole and as result 14 gallons of crude oil was released onto the roadway and into the roadside ditch.  The transport vehicle was non drivable and had to be towed from the scene. The roadway was cleaned and impacted roadside ditch was excavated to remove impacted soil and area graded to restore contouring.  The Plains driver was injured and treated at Hutchison Regional Medical Center in Hutchison, KS.
column170: Plains management communicated during a safety stand down call with field personnel the importance of safe driving.

column169: A CN mechanical employee observed icing around the protective housing of tank car # UTLX 957945 along with a gas type odor while performing switching operations at the CN Harrison Yard in Memphis, TN. The CN Dangerous Goods Team was notified and responded to the rail yard to investigate.  Upon arrival, the DGO observed a large ice buildup around the protective housing.  Upon opening the housing, ice buildup was observed around the B end liquid valve. The valve was found to not be in the fully closed position with its securement plug less than tool tight (could turn by hand) allowing the tank cars contents to leak out. The liquid valve handle was hand tightened (approximately 1/4 turn) stopping the leak. The securement plug was removed, thread sealant applied, reinstalled and tightened with a pipe wrench.  The railcar was released onto destination.

column169: SequenceEvent: Pkg was on QA rollers at beginning of AM sort with an inspection required scan (usual process and placement of pkg for us).  Sr QA Admin inspected pkg, cutting it open and pulling  out all 4 cans; no evidence of leakage but all 4 cans were dented. Pkg put back into sort. column169: XPO Logistics terminal LLR experienced a NA1760 Aluma-Brite HD release from a 55-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and containment.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of material released to a 5’ x 5’ and 10’ x 3’ areas of the trailer floor and a 10’ x 3’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas and then collected into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

It was reported that due to unknown reasons approximately .25 lb of Dynadet/Gardoclean T 5417 (Hazardous - UN1823) was released. The released product was contained to the dock floor. The SDS with the terminal and they felt comfortable cleaning the release donning the proper PPE per SDS. The released product, and damaged container were placed into a 65 gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release.

At approximately 09:00 AM a Basic Chemicals truck driver was delivering Caustic Soda to a customer site (Mosaic) located in St. James, LA. The driver met with the customer site operator, completed the “In the Interest of Safety Form” (which is a form utilized by Basic Chemical truck drivers to ensure that enough space exists in a customer tank prior to unloading), hooked up offloading hoses, and began offloading. Near the end of offloading, the driver knew the tanker trailer was getting close to being empty, so he got with the customer site operator to check the level of the storage tank again to ensure there was enough room remaining in the product storage tank. The operator checked the level of the storage tank and confirmed with the driver that there was enough space to complete the offload. Not long after the customer site operator left the area the storage tank began to overflow and the Basic Chemicals truck driver immediately shut down the flow of product. The driver got with the customer site operator to notify him of the overflow and the operator stated that the tank level indicator had been malfunctioning lately. Customer site personnel were able to clean up the spill which was estimated to be approximately 20 gallons. No injuries or damage to equipment was reported.
column170: The Basic Chemicals truck driver immediately shut down the offloading operation and notified customer site operators. The area was washed down and cleaned up. Occidental Chemical Tech Service group has been requested to reach out to the customer site (Mosaic) to discuss necessary corrections that are needed moving forward to prevent a re-occurrence. Proper repairs/replacement need to be completed to the level indicator on the product storage tank at the customer site.

On 11/08/2023, a Veolia employee from the Schenectady, NY office was unloading drums from a truck into another trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility when the employee noticed that a drum was leaking from the gasket of the lid of the 551A2 drum. The faulty gasket allowed for mineral oil to leak out of the drum. The mineral oil was used to coat the reactive lithium in the drum. No actual lithium was released from the drum.  The 551A2 lid was opened and the gasket of the drum was inspected and found to be defective and had allowed mineral oil to seep out. The gasket on the drum was replaced and the entire drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon 1A2 salvage drum. Transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued.
column170: On 11/08/2023, the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation is that the gasket on the 551A2 was defective. Though mineral oil oil leaked out of the drum, no actual hazardous materials (the lithium) was released from the drum.

Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release was contained to a small area on the side of the drum only. Contractors inspected the trailer and confirmed there was no evidence of a release onto the trailer floor but found 2 additional damaged drums that were not leaking. The impacted drum was wiped clean, and the 3 damaged drums were transferred into a metal overpack without complication. The overpacks and the rest of the cargo were secured for transport and forwarded on to the original consignee. Contractors did not collect any waste during this ER response.

column169: First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon  the  contractor’s  arrival,  personnel  observed  that the  released  material  impacted  a 10ft-by-53ft area of the trailer floor and 2ft-by-2ft area of the asphalt terminal lot under the trailer and estimated that fifty (50) gallons of material was released due to one (1) damaged/leaking 55-gallon metal drum that had been punctured by other freight. First Call Environmental personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and then wiped down all impacted packaged in the trailer with rags. The spent absorbents were gathered and containerized into three (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged 55- gallon metal drum was overpacked into one (1) 85-gallon metal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column169: Transport driver was loading his truck at Lane 2 at our Pompano Beach Terminal and there was a third party attempting to load at lane 1. The third party was having trouble and asked for help. Our transport driver continued to allow his truck to load, but failed to remain in attendance when he went to help the third party load at lane 1. When our transport driver got back to his truck, he noted that it the gauge read 95%, but he proceeded to fill out his paperwork and headed to Ft. Pierce to unload the propane rather than unloading what he had overfilled back into storage down to the AmeriGas required 85%.   When our transport driver arrived in Ft. Pierce at 11:45am, he went to look for a service technician for help on what valves to open. As they walked back to the area that his truck was at (roughly 12:00pm), the pressure relief valves activated to release built up pressure - the gauge at this time was reading well over 95% due to expansion and the ground being a unlevel. Our transport driver states that the release lasted for roughly 5 minutes, but that he was able to unload his transport when it stopped leaking.
column170: Refresher information for employee to ensure an understanding of Attendance requirements while loading and unloading per FMCSA, NFPA, and internal company guidelines. Extra check in place by the terminal operator to review documentation and verify percentage of product in transport.

On November 9, 2023 a trailer in temporary storage at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Henderson Colorado was observed to be smoking. The dock area was immediately evacuated and the Veolia emergency response team evaluated the situation.  Further investigation revealed a 55 gallon drum containing inner containers of hydrochloric acid and alkyl sulfonic acid was improperly packed. The container of sulfonic acid shifted and fell on its side during transportation resulting in a release of material which mixed with the hydrochloric acid causing a reaction and vapor release. The Veolia ER team repacked the material into two separate containers - one containing the hydrochloric acid and one containing only the alkyl sulfonic acid. The alkyl sulfonic acid drum was reloaded on the rear of the vehicle for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column170: The technical services person who improperly packed the container is no longer employed by Veolia. Veolia reviewed the training provided to all technical services employees and confirmed that proper lab packing, including chemical segregation and adding sufficient absorbent material is covered during training.

column169: Tank vehicle was traveling 35 mph in a 55 mph zone, on a rural paved road. Driver was peeling a banana when the vehicle left the paved portion of the roadway, entered the soft shoulder of the road, was pulled into the ditch and rolled. As time passed and the vehicle lay on its passenger side, diesel fuel began to trickle from the relief vents on the fill port covers. Approximately two gallons of fuel was released from the cargo tank of which approximately 2 cups reached the environment. Two shovels full of contaminated soil were removed from the scene and placed in a diesel fuel waste barrel for proper disposal.
column170: The cargo tank, tank valves and covers did their job to best contain the shipped fuel during the roll-over incident. The cause of this incident involved the driver being distracted while operating the vehicle on the highway. Company policy prohibits behaviors which cause distracted driving. Driver coaching and additional training has taken place.

column169: On November 16, 2023, at 0830 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal LJS experienced an over the road diesel fuel and hazardous cargo release due to a single vehicle rollover accident. The unit left the roadway resulting in a release to the shoulder soil. On November 16, 2023, at 0935 ET, XPO Logistics retained ERTS to manage and oversee the incident. ERTS dispatched ES&H to the site to perform all cleanup and remediation activities. On November 16, 2023, at 1230 ET, ES&H personnel arrived on site and began assisting the onsite wrecker company, Lewis Wrecker Service, with clearing the wreckage debris. The wrecker company hauled the two damaged trailers offsite after conducting a soil/debris scrape to remove as much material and debris from the ground. ES&H personnel were able to confirm approximately 25-gallon of diesel released from a damaged saddle tank along with approximately 100-gallons of UN1210 STR Steam Mat from (2) 55-gallon metal drums, and approximately 1- quart of UN3077 Cyasorb THT 7001 EF Light Stabilizer (PGIII) from a single 50-pound poly bag. The impacted soil area was confirmed to measure approximately 20’ x 30’. The contractors confirmed the majority of the cargo released to the inner trailer and freight. A roll off was utilized to containerize (20) 55-gallon metal drums of STR Steam Mat that were not releasing, along with two empty drums of this product. A total of (60) 50-pound bags of Cyasorb were individually poly wrapped and placed in the roll off. A total of (6) 5-gallon poly jugs of non-regulated PureOil Formulation K were placed into the roll off. One 55-gallon poly drum of debris, impacted grass, and soil was also generated and staged in the roll off. The roll off was then hauled to the wrecker yard. On November 17, 2023, ES&H personnel returned to the site to assess the area and complete final cleanup. ES&H located a small indent in the ground measuring 4' x 18" that was still impacted by some free-standing liquid of UN1210 STR Steam Mat. ES&H solidified the material with acid gator and collected it into their poly waste bags. Acid gator was deployed near the tree as well. An additional 17 bags of impacted mud, dirt, leaves, and acid gator were generated and removed from site. The bags were hauled to the roll off and placed inside pending overpacking. On November 20, 2023, ES&H personnel returned to the wrecker yard for waste containerizing. The (20) 55-gallon drums of UN1210 STR Steam Mat were wiped down and shrink wrapped 4 to a pallet for salvage. The two empty drums of STR Steam Mat were crushed and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum along with poly sheeting for disposal. All (60) 50-pound bags of UN3077 Cyasorb THT 7001 EF Light Stabilizer (PGIII) were containerized into 3 supersacks for disposal. The (6) 5-gallon poly jugs of PureOil Formulation K were poly wrapped to a pallet for disposal. All poly bags containing wreckage debris, mud, grass, soil, leaves, sticks, acid gator impacted with diesel & UN1210 were contain

column169: At 1736 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at XLA. It was reported that approximately 6 gallons of CCT 800 (AFCO 6055) Nitric Acid Gel Clear was released from two 5-gallon plastic jerrycans due to improper loading. The load shifted and crushed the cans. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released to a 10' x 15' area of the trailer floor due to the pails falling over in transit. The damaged pails, impacted absorbents, impacted pallets, and cleanup debris were containerized into (5) 55-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: PVS Transportation Driver had to use 3 separate hose conections to deliver product into the customer's tank. When the driver pressurized the trailer a leak developed at the dry-mate connection on the second hose. The connection was leaking for approxiamately 5 minutes in duration before the operater on site notified the driver and the flow was turned off. Floor-dry was used by the customer to absorb the spilled product.
column170: PVS Transportation management has coached the PVS Transportation driver on the importance of checking and inspecting the hoses and eqipment before and after each use. The customer was coached that the operater should have walked out the entire line as the truck is pressurized and the product starts to flow. The early detection of the leak would have reduced the amount of product spilled on the ground. The dry-mate fitting on the leaking hose has been replaced and tested to ensure the hose will not leak again.

column169: Our vehicle was traveling south on 1-95. The Town of Hope Mills, NC had attempted an arrest that led to a chase where the assailant fled to 1-95. The police continued the chase on 1-95 into a construction zone, the assailant attempted to pass our vehicle on the right where he was blocked with concrete barricades, and wedged his vehicle between our truck and the concrete barricades, causing him and our driver to crash. Our vehicle hit the concrete barricade on the right and the tank rolled over the concrete median, which gouged a small hole in two places on the tank, causing approx 1,500 gallons to spill on the roadway and soil adjacent to the road. The Fayetteville, NC hazmat team secured the area, plugged the holes, and controlled the pump out of the cargo tank, and allowed us to place absorbent booms to control the migration of the gasoline.  No photos are available for the pump out and original damage due to the HazMat team keeping everyone away from the tanker until it was pumped out. The product was leaking approximately 7-8 hours until  they could get the holes stopped up. We have hired a geologist to assist with supervising the follow up cleanup and removal of contaminated soil. That work has not begun at the time of this report.
column170: This accident should not have happened. We do not know of any way to have improved our driver's performance in handling this situation. We believe that the chase should have been aborted upon entering 1-95 and a working construction zone.

column169: At approximately 09:00 on Friday, November 3, 2023, a Basic Chemicals truck driver was delivering Hydrochloric Acid to a customer site (AZZ Inc.) located in Prairie Grove, AR. When the driver began to offload product they immediately noticed the cam-lock connection at the customers connection was dripping, so they shut down the process, cleared the line and shimmed the cam-lock ears. The driver resumed unloading a second time and noticed the fitting continued to drip so they closed the internal valve on top of the tanker trailer and replaced the gasket at the cam-lock connection. When the driver reopened the internal valve, product was released from the CPVC piping system that is connected to the internal valve of the trailer. Approximately 2 cups of product was release and spilled. No injuries or damage to equipment was reported.
column170: The driver waited for a 3rd party repair company to arrive at the customer site and make necessary repairs to the tanker trailer. The repair company arrived on-site and discovered a damaged CPVC fitting in the piping system that contributed to the minimum release of product. The repair company made the necessary repairs to the trailer and the driver was then able to safely offload the product into the customer storage tank.  This incident was reviewed with the driver by their supervisor so the driver fully understood the cause for the CPVC piping failure. Existing offloading procedures were discussed to ensure driver's understanding.

On 11/22/23, the UTLX 205951 was found in the Barstow railyard to be leaking methanol from the top of the car.  Hazmat responders isolated the car and the inspection revealed liquid leaking through the packing stem.  The valve was found in the partially open position and was missing the packing retainer nut.  The valve and release were secured with a pin.  On 11/30/23, Graymar Env returned to further secure the valve by adding a packing sleeve and retainer nut.  The car was pressure tested to verify integrity of repairs.  No leaks were found.  Shipper advised of need to get OTMA for movement to destination.

While in transit, the box was near the tail of the truck and was discovered to be leaking. The material was absorbed by the fiberboard carton and was damp. Investigation determined that the likely cause of damage was that the glass container inside the carton had broken due to excessive vibration on the tail of the truck. Once the carton had arrived back to the terminal, the material had dried from the carton. Due to the hazard of material, the packaging specs were not able to be obtained.
column170: This incident may have been prevented had the carton been loaded away from the tail of the truck or had been blocked in more securely to prevent it from excessive vibration on the tail of the unit. This incident may be used as a discussion topic in future safety meetings to illustrate the importance of proper securement of hazardous materials.

On 11/22/2023, at approximately 13:51 hours, CSX train M54121 derailed at milepost 00C 138.8.  As a result of the derailment two tank cars containing sulfur breached and released their contents which caught fire.  Additionally, an empty tank car, which last contained methanol, was determined to have breached.  Multiple other rail cars containing non-regulated materials also breached and released contents- some of which caught fire.  The shippers of hazardous materials (loaded and residue shipments) were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2023-11-22-00172).  Multiple response contractors, as well as CSX Hazardous Materials Team personnel, were responded to the incident emergently.  CSX and contractor personnel contained the fire and releases, as well as remediated the environmental impact.   Due to air quality concerns from the fire, local responders recommended that residents in the area of the derailment site evacuate.  This recommended evacuation applied to a single residence shortly after the derailment occurred and continued to expand for several hours until it included the entire town of Livingston, KY.  On 11/23/2023, at 16:00 hours, response officials lifted the evacuation.

• We had weather issues right out of the gate with freezing.  Product freezes at 50-52 degrees • Initially when he opened the trailer and customer valves (internal and external) nothing was flowing.   • Stopped, shut compressor off, closed the airline and internal and external.  Bled the pressure off the line.  No pressure was on the line or product.  Used 50 foot airline and blew heat on the QRB to warm it up.  Gave up on that.  The customer had steam so they heated the valve.  Got product flowing.   • He had 2 hoses to make delivery.  He had a wall to his right side and the back of the truck.  As such the first hose had to loop around to get it under the trailer to the wall where there was a 6” hole where part of his second hose went through the wall and connected to the customer fill line 3-4 feet inside.  After the fill line hook up there is a shut off valve roughly 8” after that.  The fill line then goes vertical to the ceiling and then over and in to the tank.     • The product (Bevrosheen) was very slushy.  This was tied to compartment 3. • At the end of the offload he saw the hose rise up and could feel the hose was light.   • He shut down and then cracked his external open and walked the line to the customer tank and shut their fill line and the internal and external valves on the trailer.   • At this point he went to bleed the pressure off the hoses but the chicago cap for the bleeder valve was froze on.  He used a screw driver to break it free.  He then lifted his pale up to the bleeder valve and opened it  ¼ of the way and nothing came out.  He continued to open it more and nothing came out.  Both he and the unloader knew that it must be blocked with frozen product.  With the bleeder valve closed now he used a screw driver to get it clear of frozen product.  It then depressurized as expected when he opened the valve.  He commented that the amount of time it took to depressurize was consistent with how long it normally takes.  The process to get the bleeder valve clear from frozen product took roughly 3-5 minutes which is noteworthy as this was time the hoses with product inside were sitting idle in the cold weather • Richard was able to safely disconnect the hose (ie – any pressure in the hose in theory is clearly gone at this point) and reducer fitting from the trailer and then capped off the reducer fitting.  He kept the reducer fitting on that end of the hose attached as the unloader was going to take the reducer and two hoses and rinse them out together for our driver.  When the unloader got the one end of the hose with the reducer fitting on it near the wash station he laid it down and uncapped it again (again no pressure coming out of it).  Our driver now moved to the customer fill line and he loosened the camlock (right side) furthest away from him first and then the left side closest too him (following protocol) which is when the hose blew off of the fill line down towards the ground with a line of product shooting up at him.
column170: We believe this was a weather related cause where product froze in the line trapping some pressure and not allowing it to be bled off.  Richard will receive additional training on wearing proper PPE going forward and strategies he can do use to help mitigate fogging issues.  He is expected to make a full recovery.
